{"abstract":[{"code":"GDate","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is a struct for calendrical calculations."}],"sections":[],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"platforms":["macOS"],"tokens":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"Date"}],"languages":["swift"]}]},{"content":[{"anchor":"overview","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDate"},{"text":" data structure represents a day between January 1, Year 1,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"and sometime a few thousand years in the future (right now it will go","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to the year 65535 or so, but [method"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.Date.set_parse"},{"text":"] only parses up to the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"year 8000 or so - just count on “a few thousand”). "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDate"},{"type":"text","text":" is meant to"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"represent everyday dates, not astronomical dates or historical dates","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"or ISO timestamps or the like. It extrapolates the current Gregorian"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"calendar forward and backward in time; there is no attempt to change","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"the calendar to match time periods or locations. "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDate"},{"type":"text","text":" does not store"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"time information; it represents a day.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"code":"GDate","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" implementation has several nice features; it is only a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"64-bit struct, so storing large numbers of dates is very efficient. It","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"can keep both a Julian and day-month-year representation of the date,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"since some calculations are much easier with one representation or the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"other. A Julian representation is simply a count of days since some","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"fixed day in the past; for ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date"},{"type":"text","text":" the fixed day is January 1, 1 AD."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"(“Julian” dates in the "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date"},{"text":" API aren’t really Julian dates in the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"technical sense; technically, Julian dates count from the start of the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Julian period, Jan 1, 4713 BC)."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDate"},{"text":" is simple to use. First you need a “blank” date; you can get a","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"dynamically allocated date from [ctor"},{"code":"GLib.Date.new","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"], or you can declare an","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"automatic variable or array and initialize it by calling [method","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.Date.clear"},{"type":"text","text":"]."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"A cleared date is safe; it’s safe to call [method"},{"code":"GLib.Date.set_dmy","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"] and the other","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"mutator functions to initialize the value of a cleared date. However, a cleared date"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"is initially invalid, meaning that it doesn’t represent a day that exists.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"It is undefined to call any of the date calculation routines on an invalid date."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"If you obtain a date from a user or other unpredictable source, you should check"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"its validity with the [method","type":"text"},{"code":"GLib.Date.valid","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"] predicate. [method"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.Date.valid"},{"type":"text","text":"]"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"is also used to check for errors with [method","type":"text"},{"code":"GLib.Date.set_parse","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"] and other functions"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"that can fail. Dates can be invalidated by calling [method"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GLib.Date.clear"},{"text":"] again.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"It is very important to use the API to access the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDate"},{"text":" struct. Often only the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"day-month-year or only the Julian representation is valid. Sometimes neither is valid."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Use the API."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"GLib also features "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDateTime"},{"text":" which represents a precise time.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date","type":"reference"},{"text":" type acts as an owner of an underlying ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDate"},{"text":" instance.","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"It provides the methods that can operate on this data type through ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/DateProtocol","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" conformance."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"Use "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date"},{"text":" as a strong reference or owner of a ","type":"text"},{"code":"GDate","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" instance.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"name":"Note","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Use "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/DateRef","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" (instead of "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date"},{"text":") for a lightweight Swift reference to an underlying ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"GDate"},{"text":" instance.","type":"text"}]}],"type":"aside","style":"note"}],"kind":"content"}],"topicSections":[{"generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init()","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(_:)-1xuni","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(_:)-46imp","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(_:)-4ld1t","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(_:)-6bawz","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(_:)-827x2","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(cPointer:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(dmy:month:year:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(gconstpointer:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(gpointer:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(julian:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(opaquePointer:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(raw:)-5r9lx","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(raw:)-8w9i2","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(retaining:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(retainingCPointer:)","doc:\/\/GLib\/documentation\/GLib\/Date\/init(retainingOpaq